==Pre-season==
===Pre-season ranking===
Going into the 1997 season, the Wolverines were ranked No. 17 in the pre-season [[Coaches' Poll]] and had experienced four consecutive four-loss seasons for the first time since the [[1934 Michigan Wolverines football team|1934]]&ndash;[[1937 Michigan Wolverines football team]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/24/sports/1997-college-football-preview-the-top-20.html?pagewanted=3|title=1997 College Football Preview; The Top 20|accessdate=2010-07-22|date=1997-08-24|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  Michigan had not won a national championship in nearly 50 years and had not played in a [[Rose Bowl Game]] since the [[1992 Michigan Wolverines football team|1992 season]].  The 1997 Michigan team was the first since the [[1969 Michigan Wolverines football team|1969 team]] to have no Rose Bowl veterans.<ref name=CHERBR>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB428A07688E5E9&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Can He End Rose Bowl Roadblock? <U+2013> Wolverines' Streets Aims For Pasadena|accessdate=December 7, 2009|date=August 19, 1997|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|page=1, Sports section|author=Bagnato, Andrew}}</ref><ref name=CFTSRRaR>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/22/sports/college-football-the-stakes-rivalry-revenge-and-roses.html|title=College Football; The Stakes: Rivalry, Revenge and Roses|accessdate=2010-07-28|date=1997-11-22|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  In early September 1997, ''[[The Columbus Dispatch]]'' wrote off Michigan, noting that "the longtime beast of the Big Ten ... has lost much of its aura" and predicting that Michigan's 1997 schedule "doesn't create a feeling that the pendulum is about to swing back."<ref name=Columbus/>

===Quarterback competition===
The months before the 1997 season opener featured uncertainty over the quarterback position.  Junior [[Scott Dreisbach]] had started 11 games for the [[1996 Michigan Wolverines football team|1996 team]],<ref name=t96>{{cite web|title=1996 Football Team|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1996fbt.htm|accessdate=2010-08-04}}</ref> but fifth-year senior Brian Griese had relieved Driesbach in the Ohio State game after Driesbach was injured and helped the team recover from a 9&ndash;0 deficit.<ref name=CFARGtLD/>  Dreisbach and Griese also faced competition from sophomore and future [[Super Bowl MVP]], [[Tom Brady]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:BNWB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EAF9A5A79B14873&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=The Chase For No. 1 <U+2013> Penn State, Washington Top Contenders|accessdate=December 8, 2009|date=August 23, 1997|work=[[The Buffalo News]]|page=C5|author=Northrup, Milt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:USTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=127E2B9B6CD4DE20&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Michigan buckles down|accessdate=December 8, 2009|date=August 20, 1997|work=[[USA Today]]|page=C5|author=Chengelis, Angelique S.}}</ref>  Shortly before the season opener, head coach Lloyd Carr announced his selection of Griese as the starting quarterback.<ref name=CFARGtLD>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/09/13/sports/college-football-a-rivalry-good-to-last-drop-or-catch.html|title=College Football; A Rivalry Good to Last Drop (Or Catch)|accessdate=2010-07-21|date=1997-09-13|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:USTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=127E2BA40BB71988&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Michigan starter: Griese|accessdate=December 8, 2009|date=September 9, 1997|work=[[USA Today]]|page=S11|author=Chengelis, Angelique S.}}</ref> 

===Receiving corps===
Despite uncertainty at quarterback, Michigan entered the 1997 season with a solid group of receivers, including [[Tai Streets]] and [[Russell Shaw]].  Analysts believed that a solid season by any of the Michigan quarterbacks could lead to a productive season in the passing game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DF3B848869FDE0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Wolverines Eager To Scale Mountain|accessdate=December 8, 2009|date=September 11, 1997|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|page=13E|author=Baptist, Bob}}</ref>  Moreover, it was anticipated that Charles Woodson, who was regarded as one of the most versatile athletes in college football,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:USTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB773117B908ACC&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=1997 PREVIEW Team-by-team outlooks [Part 1 of 2]|accessdate=December 8, 2009|date=August 22, 1997|work=[[USA Today]]|page=6E}}</ref> would play on offense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ABJB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB6C088F6BD4D20&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=He's A Turncoat, And Proud Of It Ohio Native Charles Woodson Likes Nothing Better Than Beating Buckeyes|accessdate=December 8, 2009|date=August 23, 1997|work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]]|page=C1|author=Paulk, Ralph}}</ref>  

===Holes in the offensive line=== 
The offensive line was another uncertainty for the 1997 team.  Three linemen from the 1996 team had been selected in the [[1997 NFL Draft]]: [[Center (American football)|center]] [[Rod Payne]] (3rd round, 76th overall), [[offensive guard]] [[Damon Denson]] (4th, 97) and [[defensive tackle]] William Carr (7th, 217).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/history/fulldraft?season=1997|title=1997 - Round 1|accessdate=2010-07-21|publisher=[[NFL.com]]}}</ref>  As a result, Michigan began the season with only one offensive lineman, [[offensive tackle]] [[Jon Jansen]],  who had started a game.<ref name=CFMWGMC/>  Jansen, a junior, had 25 consecutive starts entering the season.  The offensive line was further weakened when left tackle, [[Jeff Backus]], suffered a ruptured [[Vermiform appendix|appendix]].  In spring practice, offensive line coach [[Terry Malone]] made a plea for help during a staff meeting.  was searching for talent to fill in on the line.<ref name=Rising>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/09/26/sports/college-football-a-michigan-coach-keeps-rising-to-the-challenge.html|title=College Football; A Michigan Coach Keeps Rising to the Challenge|accessdate=2010-07-23|date=1997-09-26|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  To fill the holes on the offensive line, two defensive linemen, [[Steve Hutchinson (American football)|Steve Hutchinson]] and Chris Ziemann were moved to the offensive line.<ref name=Rising/>

===Strength of schedule===
Adding to the challenges facing the 1997 team, Michigan entered the season with the toughest schedule among the 112 NCAA Division I-A schools based on records from the previous year.<ref name=Columbus>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CLDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10DF3B848869FDE0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Wolverines Eager To Scale Mountain|accessdate=2009-12-08|date=1997-09-11|work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|page=13E|author=Baptist, Bob}}("Based on opponents' records last season, Michigan will play the toughest schedule of 112 NCAA Division I-A schools, facing teams that combined to win 65.8 percent of their games.")</ref>  Days before the season opener, Lloyd Carr compared the daunting schedule to an expedition to [[Mount Everest]].  Carr noted, "It's a little akin to climbing Mount Everest. But Mount Everest has been climbed. And with great preparation and determination, and great attitude, which I think our players have, I can assure you we're looking forward to it."<ref name=Columbus/>

==Season summary==
====Week 1: Colorado====
{{AFB game box start
| Title = '''Week 1: (7) Colorado at (13) Michigan'''<ref name=CvM>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores97/97256/97256338.htm|title=Colorado vs. Michigan|accessdate=2010-07-21|date=1997-09-13|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>
| Visitor = {{cfb link|year=1997|team=Colorado Buffaloes|title=Colorado}} (1&ndash;1)
| Host = Michigan (1&ndash;0)
| V1 = 0| V2 =0| V3 =3| V4 =0
| H1 = 7| H2 =3| H3 =14| H4 =3
| Date = Saturday, September 13, 1997
| Location = [[Michigan Stadium]]<br /> {{USCity|Ann Arbor|Michigan}}
| StartTime = 
| ElapsedTime = 
| Attendance = 106,474
| Weather = 
| Referee = 
}}
{{AFB game box end}}
Michigan opened the 1997 season with a home game against [[Colorado Buffaloes football|Colorado]].  Three years earlier, Colorado had defeated Michigan in [[The Miracle at Michigan]] on [[Kordell Stewart]]'s 64-yard [[Hail Mary pass]] to [[Michael Westbrook]] as time ran out.<ref name=CFARGtLD/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/25/sports/college-football-on-the-wing-of-a-prayer-colorado-shocks-michigan.html|title=College Football; On the Wing of a Prayer, Colorado Shocks Michigan|accessdate=2010-07-22|date=1994-09-25|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/15/sports/same-pass-no-catch-michigan-gets-chance-to-rewrite-history.html|title=Same Pass, No Catch: Michigan Gets Chance to Rewrite History|accessdate=2010-07-22|date=1996-09-15|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  

Michigan won the 1997 game 27 to 3, a margin that eliminated the possibility of another last-minute miracle.<ref name=CFMWGMC>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/09/14/sports/college-football-michigan-with-griese-manhandles-colorado.html|title=College Football; Michigan, With Griese, Manhandles Colorado|accessdate=2010-07-22|date=1997-09-14|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  Griese completed 21 of 28 [[forward pass]] attempts for 258&nbsp;yards and two [[touchdown]]s.  [[Tight end]] [[Jerame Tuman]] had five [[reception (American football)|receptions]] for 126&nbsp;yards.  Defensively, Michigan [[interception|intercepted]] four passes thrown by Colorado's John Hessler, while holding him to 141 yards on 15 of 39 passing.<ref name=CvM/>  

Throughout the game, Michigan relied on [[man-to-man defense]] from [[cornerback]]s Woodson and [[Andre Weathers]], [[Blitz (American football)|blitzes]] and pressure from the four-man [[defensive line]].<ref name=CFMWGMC/>  Colorado only threw against Woodson five times, and one of those passes was intercepted by Woodson at Michigan's 45-yard-line.  Griese and Tuman connected for 53 yards on the very next play.  Two plays later [[Chris Floyd (American football)|Chris Floyd]] executed a one-yard dive for the first points of the day.  Late in the second quarter, Griese completed a 29-yard pass to Woodson,<ref name=CvM/> and Kraig Baker kicked a [[field goal (American football)|field goal]] on the final play of the first half to give Michigan a 10-0 lead at halftime.<ref name=CFMWGMC/>  

Michigan opened the second half with an 89-yard, 11-play drive that included a 20-yard pass from Griese to Tuman followed by a [[roughing the passer]] penalty.  The drive ended in a 5-yard touchdown pass from Griese to [[Chris Howard (American football)|Chris Howard]].<ref name=CvM/>  In the third quarter, Michigan scored 14 points in a span of one minute and 44 seconds; the second touchdown followed a Clint Copenhaver [[interception]] that was returned to the Buffaloes' 14-yard line.<ref name=CFMWGMC/>  The touchdown was scored on a 6-yard pass from Griese to Shaw.<ref name=CvM/>  Baker closed out the scoring with a 19-yard field goal in the fourth quarter.<ref name=CvM/>

The loss was Colorado's worst defeat under head coach [[Rick Neuheisel]], its lowest point total in 101 games, and fewest yards of [[total offense]] (224) in five years.<ref name=CFMWGMC/>  It was Michigan's fifth consecutive season-opening win and fifth straight win against a top 10 team in the [[Associated Press poll]].<ref name=CvM/>  
{{clear}}

====Week 2: Baylor====
{{AFB game box start
| Title = '''Week 2: Baylor at (9) Michigan'''<ref name=BvM>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores97/97263/97263343.htm|title=Baylor vs. Michigan|accessdate=2010-07-21|date=1997-09-20|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>
| Visitor = {{cfb link|year=1997|team=Baylor Bears|title=Baylor}} (1&ndash;2)
| Host = Michigan (2&ndash;0)
| V1 = 3| V2 =0| V3 =0| V4 =0
| H1 = 7| H2 =14| H3 =7| H4 =10
| Date = Saturday, September 20, 1997
| Location = [[Michigan Stadium]]<br /> {{USCity|Ann Arbor|Michigan}}
| StartTime = 
| ElapsedTime = 
| Attendance = 106,041
| Weather = 
| Referee = 
}}
{{AFB game box end}}
In the second week of the season, Michigan defeated [[Baylor Bears football|Baylor]] 38&ndash;3 at Michigan Stadium.  Baylor scored first after running back Chris Howard fumbled on Michigan's 29-yard-line.  The Bears had a touchdown called back due to an offensive [[Holding (American football)|holding]] penalty, but kicked a 30-yard field goal.<ref name=BvM/>  Michigan took the lead with 5:39 remaining in the first quarter on a 10-yard  wide receiver [[Screen (sports)|screen play]] from Griese to Woodson.<ref name=BvM/>  Chris Howard added two touchdowns in the second quarter to give Michigan a 21-3 lead at halftime.  Howard's second touchdown capped a 14-play, 92-yard drive that consumed four-and-a-half minutes.<ref name=BvM/>

True freshman [[Anthony Thomas (American football)|Anthony Thomas]] scored on a two-yard run in the third quarter to complete Michigan's second 92-yard drive of the day.  In the fourth quarter, Woodson had a 34-yard touchdown catch called back due to a [[false start]] penalty, but [[Jay Feely]] kicked a 51-yard field goal.<ref name=BvM/>  Tate Schanski scored Michigan's final touchdown on a 1-yard run with 2:57 remaining in the game.<ref name=BvM/>

Michigan outgained Baylor 532&ndash;154 in total offense.  The Wolverines totaled 344 rushing yards, including 112 yards by Howard and 122 yards by Thomas.  [[Clarence Williams (running back born 1977)|Clarence Williams]] added 129 yards of total offense, including 77 yards rushing.<ref name=BvM/>  Griese completed 13 of 22 passes for 169 yards and no interceptions,<ref name=BvM/> and Woodson had two receptions for 45 yards.

On defense, the Wolverines held Baylor to 32 yards in the second half, allowing 3 plays on its first 4 possessions of the second half.  Woodson allowed no catches and made five unassisted [[tackle (football move)|tackles]] (three for a loss).  He played 46 downs on defense, six on [[special teams]] and five on offense.<ref name=BvM/>  The win improved Michigan to 16&ndash;6&ndash;2 against the Big 12 Conference and 9&ndash;0 in September under Carr.<ref name=BvM/>  
     
{{clear}}

====Week 3: Notre Dame====
{{AFB game box start
| Title = '''Week 3: Notre Dame at (6) Michigan'''<ref name=NDvM>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores97/97270/97270386.htm|title=Notre Dame vs. Michigan|accessdate=2010-07-21|date=1997-09-27|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><br>([[Michigan<U+2013>Notre Dame rivalry|Michigan<U+2013>Notre Dame rivalry game]])
| Visitor = [[1997 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]] (1&ndash;3)
| Host = Michigan (3&ndash;0)
| V1 = 7| V2 =7| V3 =0| V4 =0
| H1 = 0| H2 =7| H3 =14| H4 =0
| Date = Saturday, September 27, 1997
| Location = [[Michigan Stadium]]<br /> {{USCity|Ann Arbor|Michigan}}
| StartTime = 
| ElapsedTime = 
| Attendance = 106,508
| Weather = 
| Referee = 
}}
{{AFB game box end}}
For the third game of the season, Michigan faced [[Notre Dame Irish football|Notre Dame]] in the 27th match between college football's winningest programs.  Michigan won the game 21&ndash;14 in front of a crowd of 106,508, the sixth largest in the history of Michigan Stadium at that time.<ref name=CFIAGTWbSL/>  Under first year coach [[Bob Davie (American football)|Bob Davie]], Notre Dame had lost consecutive games to [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]] and [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]], and entered [[Michigan Stadium]] unranked for the first time since the creation of the AP Poll in 1936.<ref name=CFSNDCL>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/09/27/sports/college-football-struggling-notre-dame-confronts-limitations.html|title=College Football; Struggling Notre Dame Confronts Limitations|accessdate=2010-07-23|date=1997-09-27|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  Notre Dame ended the day with its first three-game losing streak in 12 years.<ref name=NDvM/>

In the first quarter, Notre Dame scored first on a 15-yard touchdown pass from [[Ron Powlus]] to Bobby Brown, culminating a 12-play, 78-yard drive.<ref name=NDvM/>  In the second quarter, the Wolverines tied the game on a 4-yard touchdown run by Clarence Williams to complete an 11-play, 68-yard drive.<ref name=NDvM/>  Notre Dame regained the lead late in the second quarter on a 98-yard drive ending in a 2-yard run by Tony Driver with 18 seconds left in the half.<ref name=NDvM/> 

Within the first 24 seconds of the second half, Griese and Streets connected on back-to-back passes of 15 and 41 yards to tie the game at 14.<ref name=NDvM/>  Michigan scored again just over five minutes later on a 14-yard run by Floyd.<ref name=NDvM/>  Michigan's defense overcame three fourth-quarter turnovers and held the Fighting Irish scoreless in the second half to preserve the 21&ndash;14 lead.  After [[Aaron Shea]] lost a fumble at the Michigan 47-yard line, cornerback [[Tommy Hendricks]] made a diving interception in the end zone with 10:34 remaining in the game.<ref name=NDvM/>  When Notre Dame recovered a loose ball two minutes later at the Wolverines 42-yard line, Michigan's defense forced a punt after a three-and-out.<ref name=NDvM/>  The Wolverines suffered a third turnover late in the fourth quarter when Griese and Chris Howard botched a handoff that Notre Dame recovered at the Michigan 28-yard line.  Notre Dame drove to the 20-yard line, but [[Glen Steele]] and [[James Hall (American football)|James Hall]] made a key stop on fourth down.<ref name=CFIAGTWbSL>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/09/28/sports/college-football-irish-are-granted-three-wishes-but-still-lose.html|title=College Football; Irish Are Granted Three Wishes, but Still Lose|accessdate=2010-07-24|date=1997-09-28|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  Howard helped Michigan run out the final 3:26 with runs of 27, seven, nine and eight yards.<ref name=NDvM/>

Notre Dame outgained Michigan in total offense by a margin of 354 yards to 345 yards.<ref name=CFIAGTWbSL/>  Notre Dame's offensive standouts were Powlus (177 passing yards) and Malcolm Johnson (106 receiving yards).  However, Notre Dame was penalized 10 times for 92 yards, including six holding infractions, one of which nullified a pass interference penalty against Woodson.<ref name=CFIAGTWbSL/>  Michigan's offensive stars of the game were Griese (16-of-22 passing for 177 yards), Howard (91 rushing yards rushing on 16 carries) and Streets (3 receptions for 77 yards).<ref name=NDvM/>
{{clear}}

====Week 4: Indiana====
{{AFB game box start
