Iowa's [[Tavian Banks]] totaled 99 yards on 19 carries, including a 16-yard third quarter run that broke [[Byron Hanspard]]'s NCAA record for fewest carries (129) to break 1,000 yards with only his 125th carry.<ref name=IvM/>   Griese who was 15 for 26 for 165 yards threw three interceptions.<ref name=IvM/> Sherman was also intercepted three times.<ref name=IvM/> Thomas had 129 yards on 20 carries.<ref name=IvM/>  Howard had 81 yards on 13 first half carries.<ref name=IvM/>  It was Michigan's fifth straight victory against Iowa and gave them a recent 8&ndash;1&ndash;1 record.  Michigan had a 35&ndash;8&ndash;4 record against Iowa overall.<ref name=IvM/>

Banks opened the scoring 91 seconds into the second quarter with a 53-yard touchdown run.<ref name=IvM/>  Griese responded by connecting with Streets for 15 yards to tie the game with 4:53 remaining.<ref name=IvM/> On Michigan's next drive, cornerback Ed Gibson intercepted Griese and returned the ball 64 yards to the Michigan 1.<ref name=IvM/> From there Michael Burger put Iowa ahead with a touchdown run with 2:27 remaining.<ref name=IvM/> On the final play of the first half, [[Tim Dwight]] had a 61-yard [[punt return]] to give Iowa a 21&ndash;7 lead.<ref name=IvM/>  Michigan tied the score with 3:11 remaining in the third quarter on a [[quarterback sneak]] on 4th-and-goal from the one by Griese.<ref name=IvM/> Iowa retook the lead on a field goal after a 72-yard [[kickoff return]] by Dwight.<ref name=IvM/> However, Griese and Tuman connected on a 2-yard pass with 2:55 remaining in the game.<ref name=IvM/>  [[Sam Sword]] intercepted Matt Sherman with 31 seconds left after Iowa had driven down to Michigan's 15 yard line.<ref name=IvM/>  After six games the Michigan defense still had a fourth quarter shutout and had allowed just three third quarter field goals.<ref name=IvM/>  Iowa had four plays for over 50 yards, including special teams.<ref name=IvM/> 
