====Week 7: Michigan State====
{{AFB game box start
| Title = '''Week 7: (5) Michigan at (14) Michigan State'''<ref name=MvMS>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores97/97298/97298346.htm|title=Michigan vs. Michigan State|accessdate=2010-07-21|date=1997-10-25|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><br>([[Paul Bunyan Trophy|Paul Bunyan Trophy game]])
| Visitor = Michigan (7&ndash;0, 4&ndash;0)
| Host = {{cfb link|year=1997|team=Michigan State Spartans|title=Michigan State}} (5&ndash;2, 2&ndash;2)
| V1 = 3| V2 =7| V3 =3| V4 =10
| H1 = 7| H2 =0| H3 =0| H4 =0
| Date = Saturday, October 25, 1997
| Location = [[Spartan Stadium (East Lansing)|Spartan Stadium]]<br /> {{USCity|East Lansing|Michigan}}
| StartTime = 12:30 pm EDT
| ElapsedTime = 
| Attendance = 79,687
| Weather = 
| Referee = 
}}
{{AFB game box end}}
This was the 90th meeting of the rival schools that have fought for the [[Paul Bunyan Trophy]] annually since 1953.<ref name=CFDBTIaSAM>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/25/sports/college-football-deciding-best-team-in-a-state-and-more.html|title=College Football; Deciding Best Team In a State, And More|accessdate=2010-07-25|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-10-25|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  Michigan State's 5&ndash;1 start was its best since the [[1966 Michigan State Spartans football team|1966 team]].<ref name=CFDBTIaSAM/>  On the strength of zero fourth quarter points and only 9 second half points, Michigan entered the game tied for first nationally in average points allowed (8.3) and in second in both yards of total offense allowed (207.7) and defensive [[pass efficiency]].<ref name=CFDBTIaSAM/>  Michigan State entered the game with a 34 points per game average, which was the schools best since the {{cfb link|year=1978|team=Michigan State Spartans|title=1978 team}}.<ref name=CFDBTIaSAM/>  Although Michigan held a 58&ndash;26&ndash;5 series edge, the home team had won each of the last five meetings and Michigan State had won 7 consecutive home games.<ref name=MvMS/> Sophomore [[linebacker]] [[Dhani Jones]] had led Michigan in tackles in each of the three previous games and was second on the defense in tackles for the season.<ref name=CFDBTIaSAM/>  Thomas entered the game with 355 rushing yards and on pace to surpass [[Jamie Morris]]'s school record for true freshman of 574 yards.<ref name=FSMDSVOS/>

Woodson and [[Marcus Ray]] each snared two interceptions and the team tied a school record with six.<ref name=FSMDSVOS>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/26/sports/football-stifling-michigan-defense-sparks-victory-over-spartans.html|title=Football; Stifling Michigan Defense Sparks Victory Over Spartans|accessdate=2010-07-25|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-10-25|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  The interceptions brought Woodson's career total to 15, which was second in school history.<ref name=FSMDSVOS/> Baker had three field goals (the third time in four weeks).<ref name=MvMS/> Michigan again shut down its opponent in the second half, holding Michigan State to 43 yards in the first 28:18 until the final drive in "[[garbage time]]" with substitutes on the field.<ref name=FSMDSVOS/> The game was only the second time Michigan State had surrendered 6 interceptions (the first since the {{cfb link|year=1958|team=Michigan State Spartans|title=1958 team}}).<ref name=FSMDSVOS/>  The Spartans could not score on the Michigan defense and were only able to produce a touchdown with a fake field goal on special teams.<ref name=FSMDSVOS/>  Although sophomore [[Sedrick Irvin]] had produced 141 yards in the first half (66 rushing and 75 receiving), he was held to 15 yards in 6 carries and 2 yards on 3 receptions in the second half.<ref name=FSMDSVOS/>

Michigan State scored on a 22-yard pass from Bill Burke to Irvin from a field goal formation.<ref name=FSMDSVOS/>  The most important play early in the game was Griese's 1-yard run with 47 seconds remaining in the first half to cap a 11-play 95-yard drive to erase the Spartans' 7&ndash;3 lead. On the drive, which started after an illegal block on a punt return put Michigan deep in its own field, Howard made a 10-yard run followed by a 51-yard run for a large part of his total of 110 yards. With 2:12 remaining in the third quarter and Michigan holding a 13&ndash;7 lead, Woodson made a leaping, one-handed interception, with his left foot landing just inside the sideline. His second interception, on the next Spartan possession, led to a touchdown by Chris Howard that established Michigan's firm control of the game. Woodson was thrown against more than any time since the opener against Colorado. Despite being stifled in the second half, the Spartans remained within 6 points at the start of the fourth quarter.<ref name=FSMDSVOS/>
{{clear}}

====Week 8: Minnesota====
{{AFB game box start
