Michigan's averaged 8.1 points allowed per game, which led the nation and they ranked third behind [[1997 Florida State Seminoles football team|Florida State]] and [[1997 North Carolina Tar Heels football team|North Carolina]] with 216.9 yards allowed per game, fifth in average rushing yards allowed with 76.7 and first in pass efficiency defense with a rating of 79.62.<ref name=OCFMSID>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/27/sports/on-college-football-michigan-spells-it-dee-fense.html|title=On College Football; Michigan Spells It Dee-fense|accessdate=2010-07-25|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-10-27|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  Minnesota had previously ruined a perfect season for a 9&ndash;0 [[1986 Michigan Wolverines football team]].<ref name=OCFMSID/>  Although Minnesota was entering the game with four conference losses against no wins, it had most recently had 1-point losses to both Penn State and Wisconsin.<ref name=CFTFIAALSS/>  Michigan had won the ten previous battles for the [[Little Brown Jug (American football)|Little Brown Jug]] between the schools.<ref name=CFTFIAALSS/> Michigan entered the game as one of seven undefeated teams in Division I-A.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/01/sports/college-football-dance-of-the-unbeatens-cougars-at-risk.html|title=College Football; Dance of the Unbeatens: Cougars at Risk|accessdate=2010-07-26|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-01|author=Wallace, William N.}}</ref>

Woodson, who played 16 offensive plays,<ref name=FADFaC/> scored on a 33-yard [[reverse play]].<ref name=CFTFIAALSS/> Howard totaled 98 yards on 20 carries and added a game-high 4 receptions for 40 yards.<ref name=MvM/>  Shea led the team with 51 yards receiving on 3 catches.<ref name=MvM/>  For Minnesota, Byron Evans had 82 yards on 17 carries.<ref name=MvM/> In the game, Michigan held its opponent without a touchdown for the fifth time in its eight games.<ref name=CFTFIAALSS/> It did so by holding Minnesota to 102 yards of total offense including just 10 yards in the second half and only 12 yards passing.<ref name=CFTFIAALSS/>  After Minnesota took their first possession 71 yards for a field goal, they only gained 31 for the rest of the game.<ref name=CFTFIAALSS/>  Minnesota had just one first down in the second half as Michigan kept its season-long fourth quarter shutout going.<ref name=MvM/>  The defense shut down Minnesota so much that Michigan started four drives in Minnesota territory in the first half.<ref name=CFTFIAALSS/>  The defense helped Michigan overcome two turnovers inside Minnesota's 5-yard-line and a missed field goal.<ref name=CFTFIAALSS>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/02/sports/college-football-the-fighting-irish-avoid-a-last-second-shocker.html|title=College Football; The Fighting Irish Avoid A Last-Second Shocker|accessdate=2010-07-26|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-02}}</ref>  The win marked the 28th in the last 30 meetings against Minnesota for Michigan.<ref name=MvM/>

Minnesota led 3&ndash;0 on Adam Bailey's 27-yard field goal after one quarter.<ref name=MvM/>  Woodson, who also had two unassisted tackles, scored on his reverse 9 seconds into the second quarter to give Michigan the lead for good.<ref name=MvM/>  Michigan also scored on a drive starting at Minnesota's 33 following a short punt. Griese connected with Thomas for 28 yards and then with [[Mark Campbell]] for a 12-yard touchdown to give Michigan its 14&ndash;3 halftime lead.<ref name=MvM/>  In the third quarter Michigan mounted a 93-yard drive that ended with a 29-yard Thomas touchdown run. Baker added a field goal in the final quarter.<ref name=MvM/>
{{clear}}

