{{AFB game box end}}
The game matched an 8&ndash;0 Michigan team against 7&ndash;0 Penn State.<ref name=FADFaC>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/05/sports/football-dominant-force-cornerback-michigan-s-woodson-gets-involved-offense.html|title=Football: A Dominant Force at Cornerback; Michigan's Woodson Gets Involved in Offense From Distant Spot|accessdate=2010-07-26|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-05|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  The day was notable as only the fourth time in the 62 year history of the AP Poll that 4 of the top 5 teams in the poll were facing each other as 8&ndash;0 Florida State and North Carolina met in an [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] battle.<ref name=CFBoU>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/05/sports/football-dominant-force-cornerback-michigan-s-woodson-gets-involved-offense.html|title=College Football; Battles of Unbeatens: Games Players Play For|accessdate=2010-07-26|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-08|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref> The November 8 battle of unbeaten and untied teams was the latest such contest in the Big Ten since 1973.<ref name=CFBoU/>  Penn State had the longest active winning streak among major college at 12.<ref name=CFBoU/> Michigan's defense ranked first among major colleges in the average of points allowed (7.5), yards per game (202.5) and pass efficiency rating (77.5).<ref name=CFBoU/>  Penn State had an active streak of three consecutive wins by four points or fewer for the first time in their 111-year history of their football program.<ref name=CFBoU/>   While Michigan's offense was averaging 27.6 points and 397 yards a game, Penn State's offense was averaging 464 yards a game, which was eighth best in Division I-A, including 240 yards rushing, which was ninth best.<ref name=CFDINMWDIF>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/04/sports/college-football-division-i-a-notebook-michigan-wolverines-defense-is-feared.html|title=College Football: Division I-A Notebaook -- Michigan; Wolverines Defense Is Feared|accessdate=2010-07-27|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-04|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  Against common foes, Northwestern and Minnesota, Penn State beat the Gophers by 1 point and the Wildcats by 3, while the Wolverines defeated them by a total of 38 points.<ref name=CFDINMWDIF/> Following the victory there was speculation that Michigan would be recognized as the number one ranked team since [[1997 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]] required [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] to beat {{cfb link|year=1997|team=Missouri Tigers|title=Missouri}}.<ref name=MvPS/>

The game was the highest attended game in [[Beaver Stadium]] history (97,498).<ref name=CFWOBPS/> The 34&ndash;8 defeat was Penn State's worst home loss in the [[Joe Paterno]] era,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/09/sports/sports-of-the-times-the-day-lloyd-carr-bought-a-little-time.html|title=Sports of The Times; The Day Lloyd Carr Bought a Little Time|accessdate=2010-07-27|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-09|author=Rhoden, William C.}}</ref> which began in 1966.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/08/sports/sports-of-the-times-with-ties-to-2-teams-flip-a-coin.html|title=Sports of The Times; With Ties To 2 Teams, Flip a Coin|accessdate=2010-07-27|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-08|author=Rhoden, William C.}}</ref> The 24&ndash;0 was also Penn States worst halftime margin in the Paterno era.<ref name=CFWOBPS/> It was also Penn State's fourth worst home loss ever.<ref name=CFWOBPS>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/09/sports/college-football-wolverines-overwhelm-bewildered-penn-state.html|title=College Football; Wolverines Overwhelm Bewildered Penn State|accessdate=2010-07-27|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-09|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref> However, Penn State scored the first fourth quarter points or second half touchdown that Michigan had surrendered all season.<ref name=CFWOBPS/>  Nonetheless, by outgaining Penn State 416&ndash;169, Michigan held Penn State to its fewest yards since its 162 yards during the [[1987 Fiesta Bowl]] against the [[1986 Miami Hurricanes football team]] when Penn State earned its most recent national championship and its fewest yards in a loss since its 156 yard performance in a 1980 21&ndash;7 loss to the [[1980 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team]].<ref name=CFWOBPS/>  By margin of victory, it was the worst home loss under Paterno, surpassing the 31&ndash;11 loss to the [[1984 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|1984 Pitt Panthers]]. Paterno's worst beating was a the 44&ndash;6 defeat that same season in the 1984 Kickoff Classic against [[1984 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]] during the last season in which the Nittany Lions did not go to a bowl.<ref name=MvPS/>

Woodson caught a 37-yard touchdown pass and helped contain Penn State's leading receiver, [[Joe Jurevicius]] to 20 yards receiving.<ref name=CFWOBPS/> [[Curtis Enis]] totaled 103 yards rushing on 18 carries including a 1-yard touchdown run with 6:12 remaining while his team was down 34&ndash;0.<ref name=MvPS/> It was Enis' fifth consecutive 100-yard effort.<ref name=CFWOBPS/> Howard rushed for 120 yards, including a 29-yard touchdown, on 22 carries.<ref name=MvPS/> He also had four catches for 41&nbsp;yards.<ref name=MvPS/> Griese posted 151 yards on 14 of 22 passing and rushed for an additional 46&nbsp;yards.<ref name=MvPS/> His counterpart [[Mike McQueary]] was held to 10-of-22 passing for 68.<ref name=MvPS/> Michigan lowered its average yards allowed 198.7, which was the lowest among major college teams since the national champion [[1992 Alabama Crimson Tide football team]] gave up 194.2 per game.<ref name=CFWOBPS/> Penn State had not gotten inside the Michigan 40-yard-line in the first 52 minutes of the game.<ref name=CFWOBPS/>  Michigan had 9 tackles for a loss, including 5 [[quarterback sack]]s and held Penn State without a successful third down conversion in 12 attempts.<ref name=CFWOBPS/>  Michigan was 7-for-15 in third down conversions and had an overall yardage edge 416&ndash;169.<ref name=MvPS/>  In the first half, Michigan had a 259&ndash;38 yards of total offense advantage and a 16&ndash;3 first downs edge without the benefit of any turnovers.<ref name=MvPS/>

On the first drive of the game, Michigan marched 53 yards on 12 plays, leading to a 29-yard field goal by Baker.  The defense then snuff Penn State by holding their next drive to minus 13 yards.<ref name=MvPS/> On the very first play of the drive [[Glen Steele]] sacked McQueary for a 10-yard loss after a fake end-around to [[Chafie Fields]].<ref name=CFWOBPS/> On third down Juaquin Feazell tackled McQueary for a 7-yard loss.<ref name=CFWOBPS/>  The offense marched 55 yards in six plays after the resulting punt, concluding with a 12-yard run by Thomas.<ref name=MvPS/>  On the first play of the drive Griese and Tuman connected for 18 yards.<ref name=CFWOBPS/> In the second quarter, Griese gaineed 40 yards on a broken play.  Then he found an uncovered Woodson, who served as a frequent decoy on fake reverses, at the 20-yard-line and Woodson easily made it into the end zone for his 37-yard touchdown, making the score 17&ndash;0.<ref name=MvPS/>  After the defense held Penn State to one yard on its next possession, the offense marched the ball 57 yards on 11 plays capped by a Griese to Tuman 8-yard pass to make the half time score 24&ndash;0.<ref name=MvPS/> In the third quarter Michigan added a 29-yard touchdown by Howard and a 42-yard field goal by Baker before Penn State posted its meaningless touchdown late in the fourth quarter..<ref name=MvPS/>
{{clear}}

====Week 10: Wisconsin====
{{AFB game box start
| Title = '''Week 10: (2) Michigan at (24) Wisconsin'''<ref name=MvW>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores97/97319/97319472.htm|title=Michigan vs. Wisconsin|accessdate=2010-07-21|date=1997-11-15|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>
| Visitor = Michigan (10&ndash;0, 7&ndash;0)
| Host = {{cfb link|year=1997|team=Wisconsin Badgers|title=Wisconsin}} (8&ndash;3, 5&ndash;2)
| V1 = 7| V2 =9| V3 =0| V4 =10
| H1 = 0| H2 =3| H3 =7| H4 =6
| Date = Saturday, November 15, 1997
| Location = [[Camp Randall Stadium]]<br /> {{USCity|Madison|Wisconsin}}
| StartTime = 
| ElapsedTime = 
| Attendance = 79,806
| Weather = 
| Referee = 
}}
{{AFB game box end}}
Michigan held the number one ranking in the AP Poll, but Florida State was number one in the coaches poll and Nebraska also remained unbeaten.  Undefeated Michigan had the inside track to the Big Ten Conference champions automatic invitation to the Rose Bowl, but one-loss Ohio State (5-1) still controlled its own destiny. The conference also had several other one-loss contenders in the mix: week 10 opponent, Wisconsin (5-1), Purdue (5-1) and Penn State (4-1).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/15/sports/college-football-rose-bowl-matchup-wide-open.html|title=College Football; Rose Bowl Matchup Wide Open|accessdate=2010-07-28|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-15|author=Litsky, Frank}}</ref>

Despite the fact that Wisconsin was without [[Ron Dayne]] who had a sprained ankle, Michigan's performance was unimpressive compared to its undefeated peers who won by wide margins: Florida State defeated [[1997 Wake Forest Demon Deacons football team|Wake Forest]] 58&ndash;7 and Nebraska defeated {{cfb link|year=1997|team=Iowa State Cyclones|title=Iowa State}} 77&ndash;14.<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/16/sports/college-football-top-ranking-and-wisconsin-isn-t-too-much-for-michigan.html|title=College Football; Top Ranking, and Wisconsin, Isn't Too Much for Michigan|accessdate=2010-07-28|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-16|author=Smith, Timothy W.}}</ref><ref name=CFSHRO>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/16/sports/college-football-seminoles-huskers-roll-on.html|title=College Football; Seminoles, Huskers Roll On|accessdate=2010-07-28|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-16}}</ref>  Also, week 11 opponent Ohio State, defeated Illinois 41&ndash;6.<ref name=CFSHRO/>  Florida State's win gave it its record-setting 11th straight 10-win season.<ref name=CFSHRO/>  The game marked the first time in its last four attempts that Michigan won a football game while ranked number one in the AP Poll.<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/>  The game had the Badgers' third-largest crowd ever (79,806).<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/>  Michigan had 204 rushing yards and 282 passing yards with no turnovers.<ref name=OCFBMINSTtR>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/17/sports/on-college-football-beating-michigan-is-no-sure-ticket-to-roses.html|title=On College Football; Beating Michigan Is No Sure Ticket to Roses|accessdate=2010-07-28|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-17|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  Wisconsin totaled 235 yards.<ref name=MvW/>

Griese had one touchdown and 254&nbsp;yards on 19 of 26 passing.<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/>  Howard had 100&nbsp;yards on 26 carries, including two touchdowns.<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/>  Floyd added 66 yards on just 6 carries.<ref name=MvW/>  Woodson picked off his nation-leading sixth interception, had 3 receptions for 28&nbsp;yards as well as a 28-yard pass completion to Griese after what ''[[The New York Times]]'' (NYT) described as a double pass, but the ''[[USA Today]]'' (USAT) described as a handoff and pass.<ref name=MvW/><ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/> Streets had 108&nbsp;yards on 5 receptions.<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/> Carl McCullough had 106&nbsp;yards on 20 carries in Dayne's place.<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/>  Wisconsin quarterback Mike Samuel also picked up some of the slack with 73 yards on 15 carries according to NYT,<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/> but only totaled 49&nbsp;yards, according to USAT.<ref name=MvW/>

Michigan took the opening drive 80 yards in 13 plays, ending with a 1-yard fourth down run by Howard. During that drive, Michigan threw in a little razzle-dazzle with a double pass play that had Griese throwing across the field to Charles Woodson, the star cornerback who often lines up as a receiver, and Woodson throwing back to Griese, who ran the ball 28 yards to the Badgers' 1 to set up the first score.<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/> In the second quarter, Griese connected with Streets for a 38-yard touchdown, which gave Michigan a 13&ndash;0 lead after Baker missed the extra point.<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/>  Wisconsin responded with a 62-yard 14-play drive that ended with a 33-yard field goal by Matt Davenport with 4:22 remaining in the half.<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/>  Again Michigan drove down to a first-and-goal situation on the 1-yard-line, but this time on fourth down they opted for an 18-yard Feely field goal to take a 16&ndash;3 lead into halftime.<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/>  Feely took over for Baker for the rest of the game after the missed extra point.<ref name=MvW/>  Wisconsin put together an 80-yard 11-play drive with Samuel [[quarterback sneak|sneaking]] in from the one.<ref name=CFTRaWITMfM/> Feely added a 24-yard field goal 1:52 into the fourth quarter.<ref name=MvW/> Then, Howard added a 4-yard touchdown run with 6:15 remaining to make it 26&ndash;10.<ref name=MvW/> Wisconsin posted a 21-yard TD pass to [[Tony Simmons (gridiron football)|Tony Simmons]] with 2:45 left, but missed the two-point conversion, leaving them 10 points behind, which was the final margin.<ref name=MvW/>
{{clear}}

====Week 11: Ohio State====
{{AFB game box start
| Title = '''Week 11: (4) Ohio State at (2) Michigan'''<ref name=OSvM>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores97/97326/97326425.htm|title=Ohio State vs. Michigan|accessdate=2010-07-21|date=1997-11-22|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><br>([[Michigan<U+2013>Ohio State rivalry|Michigan<U+2013>Ohio State rivalry game]])
| Visitor = [[1997 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] (10&ndash;2, 6&ndash;2)
| Host = Michigan (11&ndash;0, 8&ndash;0)
| V1 = 0| V2 =0| V3 =7| V4 =7
| H1 = 0| H2 =13| H3 =7| H4 =0
| Date = Saturday, November 22, 1997
| Location = [[Michigan Stadium]]<br /> {{USCity|Ann Arbor|Michigan}}
| StartTime = 
| ElapsedTime = 
| Attendance = 106,982
| Weather = 
| Referee = 
}}
{{AFB game box end}}
The Big Ten tie-breaker left the possibility that an Ohio State win coupled with two Penn State wins could send Michigan to the Rose Bowl because Ohio State had gone to the Rose Bowl the prior year and the rule book said: "If three teams are tied, and all three teams have the same winning percentage of all games played in the traditional 11-game schedule, the most recent team representing the conference shall be eliminated, and the two remaining teams shall revert to the two-team tie procedure," unless a Big Ten team ranked first or second in the polls used by the bowl alliance, overriding other tie-breaker considerations.<ref name="OCFBMINSTtR"/>  Thus, Ohio State would likely need either Wisconsin or Michigan State to beat Penn State at Penn State or Florida State to lose to the [[1997 Florida Gators football team|Florida Gators]] at [[Ben Hill Griffin Stadium|The Swamp]] in addition to overcoming its own 1&ndash;7&ndash;1 record against Michigan under Cooper.<ref name=OCFBMINSTtR/>  In each of the prior two seasons underdog Michigan teams beat undefeated Ohio State teams to conclude the Big Ten season.<ref name=CFTSRRaR/>  Since 1935, when the [[Michigan <U+2013> Ohio State football rivalry|Michigan <U+2013> Ohio State rivalry]] game was moved to be the last game of the Big Ten season for each team, 37 have had the potential to determine the conference champion.<ref name=CFTSRRaR/>  This was the eighth time that both schools were ranked among the top five.<ref name=CFTSRRaR/>  Both schools have ended four of the other school's perfect seasons during this rivalry.<ref name=CFTSRRaR/>  Michigan's entered the game with an 8.4 points average points allowed, which was the lowest by any major school in nine seasons, while Ohio State's 10.8 average ranked second.<ref name=CFTSRRaR/> However, Michigan's average of 88.2 rushing yards allowed was eighth in the nation, while Ohio State's 131.7 average was 38th best.<ref name=CFTSRRaR/> Entering the game, Howard had posted 100-yards rushing efforts in three of the last four Michigan games.<ref name=CFTSRRaR/>

Woodson led Michigan to a 20&ndash;14 victory securing its first perfect regular season since the [[1971 Michigan Wolverines football team]] by returning a punt for a 78-yard touchdown, collecting an interception, securing a 37-yard pass reception and making three tackles.<ref name=OSvM/><ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/23/sports/college-football-florida-state-tastes-the-bitters-as-michigan-smells-the-roses.html|title=College Football; Florida State Tastes the Bitters as Michigan Smells the Roses|accessdate=2010-07-28|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-23|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref> Meanwhile, Florida State lost to Florida, leaving two major unbeatens.<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/> Michigan clinched a Rose Bowl invitation against Washington State, by building a 20&ndash;0 lead and hanging on for victory.<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/> The 106,982-person crowd set a Michigan Stadium record.<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/> Griese was 14-for-25 and 147 yards,<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/> but he had no interceptions.<ref name=OSvM/>  The Wolverines only posted 189 yards of offense (45 in the second half), including only 42 rushing yards (16 in the second half).<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/> Michigan punted 11 times.<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/>  Ohio State used its quarterbacking tandem of [[Stanley Jackson (American football)|Stanley Jackson]] and [[Joe Germaine]] who both saw lots of action.<ref name=OSvM/>  The game earned a 8.7 overnight rating for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], while [[CBS]] had a 6.2 rating for the Florida-Florida State game.<ref name=TSRBADNaPtTtP/> Thomas only posted 29 yards on 14 carries but was the leading receiver with 8 catches for 77 yards.<ref name=OSvM/>

The game's first ten possessions led to nine punts and a Jackson fumble.<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/>  However on a third down and 12 yards to go situation on Michigan's 47-yard-line in the second quarter, Griese connected with Woodson for a 37-yard catch and run. Then from the 16-yard-line, Floyd took the ball down to the 1-yard-line before Thomas slipped past [[middle linebacker]] [[Andy Katzenmoyer]] for the first touchdown.<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/>  The drive covered 62 yards, but it only consumed 2:06 on the clock.<ref name=OSvM/>  After the defense held Ohio State to three plays, Woodson fielded [[Brent Bartholomew]]'s punt on the 22-yard-line and ran up the left sideline for the score with 3:43 remaining in the first half.<ref name=OSvM/> Katzenmoyer, who was also a defensive Heisman contender, blocked Baker's extra point and ran the ball back to Michigan's 30-yard-line in attempt for a two-point conversion score for the defense.<ref name=OSvM/> With Jackson reinserted at quarterback early in the third quarter, the Buckeyes advanced the ball into the Michigan end of the field. From the Wolverine 35, Jackson hit Dee Miller who was being covered by Woodson, for a completion that carried to the Wolverine 9.  However two plays later, from the 7, Jackson tried to connect with Miller again but underthrew the ball and Woodson made his seventh interception of the season &mdash; and Jackson's first.<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/> The score remained 13&ndash;0 on Ohio State's next possession when Jackson threw an interception to Weathers while in the grasp of Sword, which led to a 43-yard interception return touchdown.<ref name=OSvM/><ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/>  Subsequently, Germaine connected with [[David Boston]] against Woodson on a 56-yard touchdown pass.<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/> Gary Berry forced a fumble during a sack of Griese that was recovered by Jerry Rudzinski at the Michigan 7 and returned to the 2. [[Pepe Pearson]], who had 80 yards on 17 carries,<ref name=OSvM/> scored on the next play on a 2-yard run.<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/> But Michigan preserved the victory when defensive end Glen Steele twice sacked Joe Germaine on the final possession and had another tackle for a loss.<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/> [[Ian Gold]] deflected Germaine's fourth-down pass from the Ohio State 16 with 42 seconds to play.<ref name=CFFSTtBaMStR/>

At the conclusion of the game Griese was carried off the field by his teammates.<ref name=OSvM/> Following the victory Michigan became the consensus number one team in the country with 69 of 70 first place votes in the AP Poll and 46 of 62 in the coaches Poll.  Although both #2 Nebraska and #3 [[1997 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]] had conference championship games remaining neither was expected to overtake Michigan in the polls even with a victory.  Thus, the Rose Bowl seemed set to have its first consensus number one participant since the [[1980 Rose Bowl]].<ref name=OCFDaDCaM>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/24/sports/on-college-football-dust-and-doubts-clear-at-michigan.html|title=On College Football; Dust and Doubts Clear at Michigan|accessdate=2010-07-28|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-24|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  Following the game, when asked if he was the best player in the country, Woodson responded: "I think so, and I try to prove that every game".<ref name=OSvM/>
{{clear}}

====Award season====
[[File:Woodson March 08.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Charles Woodson]] (pictured in 2008)]]
During the 1997 award season, Charles Woodson became one of the most honored players in Michigan history.  He was selected as Michigan's Most Valuable Player, a first-team All-Big Ten player and a first-team All-American. On December 1, 1997, he received the [[Walter Camp Award]] as the college football ''Player of the Year''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/02/sports/plus-college-football-woodson-wins-camp-award.html|title=Plus: College Football; Woodson Wins Camp Award|accessdate=2010-07-29|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-12-02}}</ref>  On December 11, 1997, Woodson also won the [[Bednarik Award]] as top defensive player and the [[Jim Thorpe Award]] as top defensive back.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/12/sports/colleges-football-manning-is-voted-best-all-round.html|title=College Football; Manning Is Voted Best All-Round|accessdate=2010-07-29|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-12-12}}</ref>  By a margin of 55 votes out of 2,500 votes cast, Woodson was beaten by [[Peyton Manning]] for the [[Maxwell Award]].  The award season culminated with the [[Heisman Trophy]].  Woodson was invited to the [[Downtown Athletic Club]] for the Heisman announcement along with fellow finalists Manning, [[Ryan Leaf]], and [[Randy Moss]].<ref name=CFHHGFaIC>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/13/sports/college-football-heisman-hopefuls-gather-for-an-intriguing-choice.html|title=College Football; Heisman Hopefuls Gather For an Intriguing Choice|accessdate=2010-07-29|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-12-13|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  Woodson won the Heisman, edging Manning by a margin of 1815&ndash;1543 points and 433&ndash;281 first place votes. He became the first predominately defensive player to receive the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/14/sports/college-football-woodson-fulfills-unlikely-dream-receives-heisman-trophy.html|title=College Football; Woodson Fulfills an Unlikely Dream, and Receives the Heisman Trophy|accessdate=2010-07-29|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-12-14|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>

Other Michigan players recognized in the 1997 award season included first-team All-Americans [[Glen Steele]] and [[Jerame Tuman]].  Ten members of the team were honored as All-Big Ten Conference selections, and [[running back]] [[Anthony Thomas (American football)|Anthony Thomas]] was named the [[Big Ten Conference football individual honors#Freshman of the Year|Big Ten Freshman of the Year]]. 

Head coach Lloyd Carr won the [[Walter Camp Coach of the Year Award]], the [[George Munger Award]], and the [[Paul "Bear" Bryant Award]].

====Rose Bowl: Washington State====
{{AFB game box start
| Title = '''Bowl game: (7) Washington State at (1) Michigan'''<ref name=WSvM>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores98/98001/98001308.htm|title=Washington State vs. Michigan|accessdate=2010-07-21|date=1998-01-01|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><br>([[1998 Rose Bowl]])
| Visitor = [[1997 Washington State Cougars football team|Washington State]] (10&ndash;2)
| Host = Michigan (12&ndash;0)
| V1 = 7| V2 =0| V3 =6| V4 =3
| H1 = 0| H2 =7| H3 =7| H4 =7
| Date = Thursday, January 1, 1998
| Location = [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]]<br /> {{USCity|Pasadena|California}}
| StartTime = 
| ElapsedTime = 
| Attendance = 101,219
| Weather = 
| Referee = 
|TVAnnouncers=[[Bob Griese]] and [[Keith Jackson]]
|TVStation=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] 

}}
{{AFB game box end}}
The game matched the number one defense in the nation against the number two offense &mdash; Michigan averaged 206.9 yards allowed, while Washington State has averaged 42.5 points and 502.1 yards a game, which only trailed Nebraska in each category.<ref name=OCFDaDCaM/> Washington State, which featured Leaf and a five-wideout offense,<ref name=TSRBADNaPtTtP/> had established [[Pacific-10 Conference]] passing records for 3,637 yards and 33 touchdowns, while Michael Black ran for 1,235 yards (second best in the conference).<ref name=FMAtSaHtHO/> The Rose Bowl national television broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] featured two interesting connections: [[Bob Griese]] would be an announcer while his son Brian quarterbacked Michigan, and [[Keith Jackson]] would also be announcer of a game by his alma mater for whom he had previously served as the radio and television voice in the 1950s.<ref name=TSRBADNaPtTtP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/25/sports/tv-sports-rose-bowl-announcers-don-t-need-a-program-to-tell-the-players.html|title=TV Sports; Rose Bowl Announcers Don't Need a Program to Tell the Players|accessdate=2010-07-28|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1997-11-25|author=Sandomir, Richard}}</ref> The game marked Michigan's first Rose Bowl since the [[1993 Rose Bowl]].<ref name=OSvM/> It was Washington State's first visit to the Rose Bowl since 1931.<ref name=CFHHGFaIC/> Both teams received $9.5 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|9.5|1998|r=1}}}} million in current dollar terms) for appearing in the game.<ref name=FMAtSaHtHO>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/01/sports/football-michigan-approaches-the-summit-and-hopes-to-hang-on.html|title=Football; Michigan Approaches the Summit, and Hopes to Hang On|accessdate=2010-07-29|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1998-01-01|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  Going into the game, Michigan held a 68&ndash;1 and 53.5&ndash;8.5 first place vote lead in the AP and Coaches Polls over fellow unbeaten Nebraska, respectively.<ref name=FMAtSaHtHO/>  Thus, it was predicted that a weak win coupled with a strong January 2, [[1998 Orange Bowl]] victory by Nebraska, could lead to split recognition as national champion.<ref name=FMAtSaHtHO/>  The day before the game Washington State coach [[Mike Price]] was bedridden with the flu.<ref name=FMAtSaHtHO/>

[[File:2008-1226-Pasadena-008-RoseBowl.jpg|thumb|left|Michigan ended its season at the [[Rose Bowl]]. (pictured in 2008)]]
Griese, who was voted Rose Bowl MVP, led Michigan to a 379 yards on offense, which nearly equaled the 398 yards gained by Washington State.<ref name=CFMBVaCtN1/> Griese completed 18 of 30 passes for 251 yards, including 3 touchdown passes: 53 and 58 yards to Streets and a 23-yard pass to Tuman with 11:21 remaining for the games final margin of victory.<ref name=CFMBVaCtN1/>  Leaf totaled 331 yards passing which was fifth highest in Rose Bowl history by completing 17 of 35 passes.<ref name=CFMBVaCtN1/> Black injured his [[calf muscle]] and was held to 24&nbsp;yards on 7 carries, while the team totaled just 67&nbsp;yards.<ref name=CFMBVaCtN1/> Streets had 4 receptions for 127 yards.<ref name=WSvM/>  Woodson had an interception and key offensive contributions late in the game.<ref name=WSvM/>

In the first quarter, Washington State downed a punt at the 1 and forced a punt without a first down.  After regaining possession at the Wolverines 47, Leaf connected with McKenzie on a 15-yard play to take a 7&ndash;0 lead with 3:07 remaining.<ref name=WSvM/> Michigan moved the ball to the Washington State 37 before punting. Leaf marched the Cougars to the Michigan 14, but Woodson intercepted him in the end zone.<ref name=WSvM/>  The teams traded punts before Griese found Streets in stride on the right sideline for a 53-yard TD pass to tie the game with 7:08 left in the first half.<ref name=WSvM/> Leaf opened the second half with a 99-yard drive for a go-ahead touchdown to take a 13&ndash;7 lead after the extra point was blocked.<ref name=WSvM/>  Key plays on the drive included a 19-yard pass Shawn McWashington and a 30-yard pass Kevin McKenzie to reach the Michigan 38.  One play later, Leaf connected with McKenzie for 20 more yards.<ref name=WSvM/>  Then Shawn Tims took a [[reverse play]] 14 yards for the score with 8:33 remaining in the third quarter.<ref name=WSvM/> On the ensuing possession, Michigan mixed four runs by Howard with a pair of short passes to Shaw before Griese found Streets for a 58-yard play-action pass TD to take a 14&ndash;13 lead with 5:07 left.<ref name=WSvM/>  After a punt by Washington State, Griese led a 14-play 77-yard drive that ended with a Tuman 23-yard play-action TD pass with 11:21 to go for a 21&ndash;13 lead.<ref name=WSvM/> In the fourth quarter Leaf converted a 3rd-and-18 play from his own 12 by connecting with McKenzie for 19 yards. Then a 42-yard pass to [[DeJuan Gilmore]] moved the ball to the Michigan 27. Washington State settled for a [[Rian Lindell]] 48-yard field goal with 7:25 to play to make the score 21&ndash;16.<ref name=WSvM/> Michigan started a drive that included four consecutive third down conversions and consumed most of the clock.  The conversions were as follows: a 3rd-and-11 Griese scrambled to the Michigan 29; a 3rd-and-7 lateral to Woodson who faked a pass before running eight yards to keep the drive alive; a 3rd-and-6 13-yard pass to Shaw; and a 3rd-and-7 pass to Woodson taking the ball to the Washington State 33.<ref name=WSvM/>  A pooch punt by Feely from field goal formation left Washington on its own 7-yard-line with 29 seconds remaining.<ref name=WSvM/> The game ended in confusion with Leaf, who announced he would hold a press conference to announce his intent to forgo his senior season and enter the [[1998 NFL Draft]], being deemed to late in an attempt to spike the ball to stop the clock for a last play.<ref name=CFMBVaCtN1/>  The drive began at the Cougar 7-yard-line with 16 seconds left to play.<ref name=CFMBVaCtN1/> Leaf completed a 46-yard pas to Nian Taylor to move the ball to the Michigan 47.<ref name=CFMBVaCtN1/>  Washington State drew an illegal formation penalty with 9 seconds remaining, but executed a hook and lateral play for 26-yards to the Michigan 26, with a 8-yard catch by Love Jefferson and an 18-yard run by Jason Clayton who was tackled by Weathers and Jones.<ref name=CFMBVaCtN1/>  With 2 seconds to play the clock was stopped to move the chains.<ref name=CFMBVaCtN1/> With no timeouts left, Leaf spiked the football, but Dick Burleson, the referee from the Southeastern Conference crew, shook his head as Leaf contested the decision.<ref name=CFMBVaCtN1>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/02/sports/college-football-michigan-grasps-victory-and-claim-to-no-1.html|title=College Football; Michigan Grasps Victory, and Claim to No. 1|accessdate=2010-07-29|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1998-01-02}}</ref>  Michigan's victory evened the series between the Pac-10 and Big 10 in the Rose Bowl at 26 wins apiece.<ref name=WSvM/>

Following the game, Michigan needed to wait a few days for the final polls.<ref name=CFMBVaCtN1/> On January 4, it was revealed that Nebraska had overtaken Michigan by 4 points and 2 first place votes in the coaches poll to earn a split in the major national polls.<ref name=FWN1RAiaTS>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/04/sports/football-who-s-no-1-results-are-in-and-they-re-split.html|title=Football; Who's No. 1? Results Are in, and They're Split|accessdate=2010-07-29|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1998-01-04|author=Moran, Malcolm}}</ref>  Nebraska had beaten Tennessee 42&ndash;17 and totaled 534 yards of total offense, including 409 rushing yards and an Orange Bowl record-setting 206 rushing yards by [[Ahman Green]].<ref name=FWN1RAiaTS/> Michigan held on to a 51.5&ndash;18.5 final first place vote lead in the AP Poll, but had a 32&ndash;30 deficit in the coaches poll.<ref name=FWN1RAiaTS/>  Since the 1969 permanent creation of the final post bowl game AP poll, no winning number 1 team had lost its lead following a Bowl game, but the [[1990 Colorado Buffaloes football team]] had lost the coaches poll to [[1990 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]] following a 10&ndash;9 [[1991 Orange Bowl]] victory over [[1990 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]].<ref name=FWN1RAiaTS/>  In addition to bowl game victory margins, [[Tom Osborne]]'s retirement and the Big Ten's cumulative 2&ndash;5 bowl game record were considered factors leading to the split polls.<ref name=FWN1RAiaTS/>  

{{clear}}

==Statistical achievements==
Michigan's 1997 defense set the NCAA Division I FBS record for fewest yards allowed per pass completion (8.8 yards per completion, 100-149 completions)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/football_records/DI/2009/2009FBS.pdf|title=2009 Division I Football Records Book: Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) Records|accessdate=2010-07-09|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|page=28}}</ref>  Over the course of the 1997 season, including conference and non-conference games, Michigan's defense led the Big Ten Conference in most statistical categories, including rushing defense (89.0 yards per game), passing defense (133.8 yards per game), passing defense efficiency (81.8 points per game), total defense (222.8 yards per game) and scoring defense (9.5 points per game).<ref name=BGCMG58>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/FullFBMG|title=Big Ten Conference Football Full Media Guide|accessdate=2010-07-08|date=2010-01-05|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]/[[Big Ten Conference]]|pages=56<U+2013>58}}(Michigan also led the Big Ten with 31 quarterback sacks in conference games, though Minnesota led the conference with 38 sacks in all games.</ref>  

Michigan's 1997 season totals in total defense and scoring defense are the lowest marks among all Big Ten football teams since the 1985 season.<ref name=BGCMG58/>  The last Big Ten team with a lower scoring defense mark was the [[1985 Michigan Wolverines football team|1985 Michigan team]] that held opponents to 6.8 points per game.<ref name=BGCMG58/>  Including the 1997 season, Michigan won the Big Ten statistical championship in rushing defense six times in eight years from 1990 to 1997.<ref name=BGCMG56>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/big10/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/FullFBMG|title=Big Ten Conference Football Full Media Guide|accessdate=2010-07-08|date=2010-01-05|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]/[[Big Ten Conference]]|page=56}}</ref>  

On offense, quarterback [[Brian Griese]] set Michigan single-season passing records with 193 pass completions and 307 pass attempts.  In each case, Griese surpassed records set by [[Todd Collins (quarterback)|Todd Collins]] in 1993; [[Tom Brady]] broke both of Griese's records in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/fbl-record-100509.pdf|title=Record Book|accessdate=2010-07-10|date=2009-01-05|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|pages=120&ndash;123}}</ref>

